code_id: ramanujan_tensor_product
physical: qubits
logical: qubits

name: 'Ramanujan tensor-product'

##Is there a concise way to qualitatively describe how the code is defined and/or distance balancing? Please give this a shot; it would make for an important and informative part of this entry.
##Describe why it is parents or cousins.

# First reference with the code (optional).
introduced: '\cite{arXiv:2004.07935}'

description: 'A quantum codes constructed from Ramanujan quantum codes and an asymptotically good classical LDPC code using distance balancing. Ramanujan quantum codes are defined using Ramanujan complexes which are simplicial complexes that generalise Ramanujan graphs. \cite{arXiv:2004.07935} proved that in principle a LSV complex can yield quantum LDPC code with \(d_x =\Omega(log^j n)\) and \(d_z = \Omega (n)\). Combining the quantum code obtained from Ramanujan complex and a good classical LDPC code yields, using the method of distance balancing, a new quantum code that is defined on a 2-dim chain complex. The new code's length, dimension and distance depends on the input codes.'

protection: 'For 2D Ramanujan complexes, codes protect against errors with minimum distance \(D = \Omega(\sqrt(N log(N))\). For 3D Ramanujan complexes, codes protect against errors with minimum distance \(D= \Omega(N^{1/2}\log(N))\).'

# This field starts a list of specific labeled subfields; do not leave it
# empty. If empty, comment out.
features:

  rate: 'For 2D, the rate is \(\Omega(\sqrt(\frac{1}{N\log(N)}))\), with minimum distance \(D = \Omega(\sqrt(N log(N))\). For 3D, the rate is \(\Omega(\frac{1}{\sqrt(N)\log(N))\) with minimum distance \(d \geq \sqrt(n) \log(n)\).'

